<subSubSection lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="14" pageNumber="39" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="14" pageNumber="39">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph lastPageId="15" lastPageNumber="40" pageId="14" pageNumber="39">
The family 
<taxonomicName genus="Pleosporaceae" lsidName="Pleosporaceae" pageId="14" pageNumber="39" rank="genus">Pleosporaceae</taxonomicName>
was introduced by 
<bibRefCitation pageId="14" pageNumber="39">Nitschke (1869)</bibRefCitation>
and is the largest family of the order 
<taxonomicName genus="Pleosporales" lsidName="Pleosporales" pageId="14" pageNumber="39" rank="genus">Pleosporales</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Hyde, KD" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="29" pageNumber="54" pagination="1 - 313" title="Families of Dothideomycetes." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-013-0263-4" volume="63" year="2013">Hyde et al. 2013</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Ariyawansa, HA" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="27" pageNumber="52" pagination="85 - 139" title="Towards a natural classification and backbone tree for Pleosporaceae." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-015-0323-z" volume="71" year="2015 b">Ariyawansa et al. 2015b</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Liu, JK" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Diversity" pageId="32" pageNumber="57" pagination="75 - 99" title="Ranking higher taxa using divergence times: a case study in Dothideomycetes." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-017-0385-1" volume="84" year="2017">Liu et al. 2017</bibRefCitation>
). Members of this family can be endophytes, aquatic or terrestrial saprobes, plant 
<pageBreakToken pageId="15" pageNumber="40" start="start">pathogens</pageBreakToken>
or opportunistic animal pathogens (
<bibRefCitation pageId="15" pageNumber="40">Sivanesan 1984</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Carter, E" journalOrPublisher="Journal of Clinical Microbiology" pageId="27" pageNumber="52" pagination="5419 - 5423" title="Fatal cerebral phaeohyphomycosis due to Curvularia lunata in an immunocompetent patient." url="https://doi.org/10.1128/JCM.42.11.5419-5423.2004" volume="42" year="2004">Carter and Boudreaux 2004</bibRefCitation>
). A backbone tree for 
<taxonomicName genus="Pleosporaceae" lsidName="Pleosporaceae" pageId="15" pageNumber="40" rank="genus">Pleosporaceae</taxonomicName>
was provided by 
<bibRefCitation author="Ariyawansa, HA" journalOrPublisher="Fungal Divers" pageId="27" pageNumber="52" pagination="1 - 248" title="Fungal diversity notes 111 - 252: taxonomic and phylogenetic contributions to fungal taxa." url="https://doi.org/10.1007/s13225-015-0346-5" volume="75" year="2015 a">Ariyawansa et al. (2015a)</bibRefCitation>
. In this study, 
<taxonomicName class="Dothideomycetes" family="Pleosporaceae" genus="Alternaria" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Fungi" lsidName="Alternaria burnsii" order="Pleosporales" pageId="15" pageNumber="40" phylum="Ascomycota" rank="species" species="burnsii">Alternaria burnsii</taxonomicName>
is reported from a 
<taxonomicName class="Liliopsida" family="Pandanaceae" genus="Pandanus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Pandanus" order="Pandanales" pageId="15" pageNumber="40" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Pandanus</taxonomicName>
sp. host in Thailand.
</paragraph>
